"Donnelly A., Cooney T., Jennings E., Buscardo E., Jones M.","Response of birds to climatic variability; Evidence from the western fringe of Europe",2009,"International Journal of Biometeorology","53","3",,"211","220",,,10.1007/s00484-009-0206-7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-65049092127&partnerID=40&md5=80fb595ceaea6110147999416497a6fe","Department of Botany, School of Natural Sciences, Trinity College Dublin, Dublin 2, Ireland","Donnelly, A., Department of Botany, School of Natural Sciences, Trinity College Dublin, Dublin 2, Ireland; Cooney, T., Department of Botany, School of Natural Sciences, Trinity College Dublin, Dublin 2, Ireland; Jennings, E., Department of Botany, School of Natural Sciences, Trinity College Dublin, Dublin 2, Ireland; Buscardo, E., Department of Botany, School of Natural Sciences, Trinity College Dublin, Dublin 2, Ireland; Jones, M., Department of Botany, School of Natural Sciences, Trinity College Dublin, Dublin 2, Ireland","Ireland's geographic location on the western fringe of the European continent, together with its island status and impoverished avifauna, provides a unique opportunity to observe changes in bird migration and distribution patterns in response to changing climatic conditions. Spring temperatures have increased in western Europe over the past 30 years in line with reported global warming. These have been shown, at least in part, to be responsible for changes in the timing of life cycle events (phenology) of plants and animals. In order to investigate the response of bird species in Ireland to changes in temperature, we examined ornithological records of trans-Saharan migrants over the 31-year period 1969-1999. Analysis of the data revealed that two discrete climatic phenomena produced different responses in summer migrant bird species. Firstly, a number of long-distance migrants showed a significant trend towards earlier arrival. This trend was evident in some species and was found to be a response to increasing spring air temperature particularly in the month of March. Secondly, (1) a step change in the pattern of occurrences of non-breeding migrant bird species, and (2) an increase in the ringing data of migrant species were found to correlate with a step change in temperature in 1987-1988. These results indicate that, for migrant bird species, the impact of a sudden change in temperature can be as important as any long-term monotonic trend, and we suggest that the impact of step change events merits further investigation on a wider range of species and across a greater geographical range. © 2009 ISB.","Climate variables; Migratory birds; Phenology; Step change; Western Europe","acclimatization; animal; article; biological model; bird; climate; Ireland; physiology; population migration; season; Acclimatization; Animal Migration; Animals; Birds; Climate; Ireland; Models, Biological; Seasons; Animalia; Aves",,,,,,"Alheit, J., Mollmann, C., Dutz, J., Kornilovs, G., Loewe, P., Mohrholz, V., Wasmund, N., Synchronous ecological regime shifts in the central Baltic and the North Sea in the late 1980s (2005) ICES Journal of Marine Science, 62 (7), pp. 1205-1215. , DOI 10.1016/j.icesjms.2005.04.024, PII S1054313905001487, Influence of Climate Change on North Atlantic Fish Stocks; Beaugrand, G., The North Sea regime shift: Evidence, causes, mechanisms and consequences (2004) Progress in Oceanography, 60 (2-4), pp. 245-262. , DOI 10.1016/j.pocean.2004.02.018, PII S0079661104000308; Both, C., Visser, M.E., Adjustment to climate change is constrained by arrival date in a long-distance migrant bird (2001) Nature, 411 (6835), pp. 296-298. , DOI 10.1038/35077063; Both, C., Bouwhuis, S., Lessells, C.M., Visser, M.E., Climate change and population declines in a long-distance migratory bird (2006) Nature, 441 (7089), pp. 81-83. , DOI 10.1038/nature04539, PII NATURE04539; Buishand, T.A., Some methods for testing the homogeneity of rainfall records (1982) J Hydrol (Amst), 58, pp. 